<proposition xml:id="prop-2-4">
  <title>The Division Algorithm</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>a,b\in \Z</m> where <m>b &gt; 0</m>, then there exists unique integers <m>q,r</m> satisfying 
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>0\le r &lt; b</m> and
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>a=bq+r</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol> 
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a proof by cases.  If <m> a \le b </m> then we are done (why???).  So then assume <m> a&gt;b </m>.  Consider the set 
      
      <me> 
        S = \{a-bk \mid  k \in \Z \text{ and } a-bk &gt; 0 \}
      </me>

      The set <m>S</m> is nonempty (why???).  The set <m>S</m> has a minimal element (why???).  Call this minimal element <m>r</m>.  Show that this <m>r</m> has the desired properties.
      You may find Definition <xref ref="definition-well-ordered"/> and Definition <xref ref="definition-well-ordered"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>




</section>